May be an image of text that says '12 signs we may be struggling with low self-esteem @millennial.therapist/ Sara Kuburic We second guess ourselves We feel like 'fraud' We seek external validation We are sensitive to criticism We find it difficult to make decisions We value other people' opinions over our own We always apologize (even when it's not our fault) We withdraw from people We are scared to show people who we are We don't set boundaries out of fear of rejection We struggle to accept a compliment We compare ourselves to others'.

node.text:
it’s normal to struggle with our self-esteem from time to time. Life is tough and our society is not always affirming of our worth. Just remember, you don’t need to earn your value – you just need to recognize it ❤️

May be an image of text that says 'the criticized child: @millennial.therapist/SaraKuburic Sara Kuburic We constantly criticize ourselves We frequently judge others We strive to be perfect We perceive vulnerability as weakness We don't trust ourselves to make decisions We have hard time showing compassion (to self or others) We seek external validation We struggle to accept a compliment We avoiding doing things we can fail at We are hard on ourselves We are hyper-sensitive to criticism from others'.

node.text:
Being overly criticized as a child will manifest in the relationships we build with ourselves and with others. We often become adults who have internalized the critical voice of our caregivers. It’s time to change the narrative ❤️ 

#millennialtherapist

node.text:
Self-confidence is trusting our ability or capacity to do something successfully (achieve a goal, accomplish a task, attract attention, etc.). It’s important to note that someone’s trust in their ability doesn’t always translate to self-esteem or self-love. Why? Because we can value a certain capacity/trait but still not value who we are as a whole. 


The most common topic surrounding self-confidence is related to the way we look. In the Body Shop’s Global Self-Love Index women said that self-image concerns lessens their confidence, as does seeing models in advertisements or influences/celebrities on social media. It also shows that women with high self-love think that their relationships and the state of the world are more important than their appearance and how others see them.


To learn more, check out @thebodyshop Self-Love Campaign!
